Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

DEFENDANT MUST POST $500 CASH

Defendant shall not possess or consume alcohol. Defendant is not to enter any bars, taverns, or liquor stores. Defendant shall not possess or use illegal drugs or drug paraphernalia. Defendant will not possess any firearms, ammunition or other weapons. Defendant is to be booked and printed within twenty-four (24) hours. Defendant will not in any way contact or attempt to contact any victim(s) listed and will avoid their residence/place of employment or any place they are located and will avoid causing any other person, other than defendant's attorney, from doing so on defendant's behalf.  The term "no contact" is hereby defined as through the mail, by telephone, by way of electronic device, in person, or through a third party.  VICTIM(S)/RESIDENCE(S): NO CONTACT WITH K.M. OR RESIDENCE. Defendant shall personally ensure that payments are made under any Order for Income Withholding if the Court appoints an attorney for the defendant.

Attorney Jason Daane appeared specially. SPD needs more time to appoint. Victim could not be present today, asking no contact be lifted. State objects.
Adjourned initial appearance scheduled for November 2, 2022 at 01:15 pm.

Wife, Susan Paredes Hernandez makes statement to court as to what happened. Victim K.M. also in court and makes a statement. Further discussion, court reduces bond to $5000 cash. No contact with S.P.H. removed, no contact with K.M. remains. Minutes filed. Initial appearance on 10/25/2022 at 1:15 pm.
